cs.DL, cs.IR, cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.CR 

This paper analyzes patterns of author contributions in scientific manuscripts, which is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. The most likely category is cs.DL (Digital Libraries), as the paper discusses the challenges of evaluating authors in an increasingly interdisciplinary and complex environment, which is relevant to the management and organization of digital scientific literature. The paper also discusses the role of metrics in evaluating authors, which is relevant to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Additionally, the paper analyzes data from PLoS One, which is a multidisciplinary open access journal, making it relevant to cs.CY (Computers and Society) and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
